## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three compounding bugs** in this component that work together to cause catastrophic listener accumulation. Here's the full breakdown.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
}); // <-- no [] here
```

Without a dependency array, `useEffect` re-runs after **every single render**. The scroll handler calls `setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, and `setLastScrollY` — each of those triggers a re-render, which triggers the effect again, which registers *more* listeners, which cause more renders:

```
Mount → addEventListener (×2)
Scroll → setState → re-render → addEventListener (×2 more)  [now 4 total]
Scroll → setState → re-render → addEventListener (×2 more)  [now 6 total]
Scroll → setState → re-render → addEventListener (×2 more)  [now 8 total]
...and so on, unbounded
```

After a few hundred scroll events the browser is firing dozens of handlers per pixel of scroll movement.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Survive Unmount)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

Even if the dependency array were fixed, when the user navigates away React unmounts the component — but the listeners attached to `window` are **not tied to the component's lifecycle**. They keep running forever, holding closure references to the component's state setters, which in turn hold references to the component's fiber and React internal structures. The garbage collector can never reclaim any of it.

**Each navigation away-and-back stacks another full set of ghost listeners** on `window`, all of them updating state for a component that no longer exists.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// ❌ New function object created every call — unreachable for cleanup
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });

// Even if you tried to clean up, this would silently do nothing:
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // different reference!
```

`removeEventListener` identifies handlers by **referential equality** — it must receive the *exact same function object* that was passed to `addEventListener`. Anonymous arrow functions create a new object every time they're evaluated, so there is no way to unregister them after the fact. Named references stored in variables are the only solution.

---

## Bug #4 — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY` (Logic Bug)

Even after fixing the above, there's a subtler correctness bug. `lastScrollY` is a state variable, so the scroll handler captures its value from the render in which the effect ran. With `[]` as the dependency array, it gets frozen at `0` forever:

```jsx
// ❌ lastScrollY will always be 0 inside this closure
const [lastScrollY, setLastScrollY] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        // lastScrollY is always the stale initial value: 0
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
    });
}, []); // captures lastScrollY = 0 at mount, never updates
```

The fix is a `useRef`, which is mutable and always reflects the latest value without causing re-renders.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects** — it mounts → unmounts → remounts every component to help surface exactly this class of bug. Without cleanup, you see handlers registered twice before any user interaction even occurs. In production (where Strict Mode doesn't double-invoke), the bug is still present but accumulates more slowly, which is why users only notice it after navigating back and forth several times.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ useRef instead of useState: mutable, always current, no stale closure,
    //    and updating it doesn't trigger a re-render
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions so removeEventListener can target the exact same reference
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // ✅ Read from ref — always the latest value, never stale
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');

            // ✅ Write to ref — synchronous, no re-render, no closure trap
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;

            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup: same named references → removeEventListener actually works
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array: register once on mount, clean up on unmount — never re-registers

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary Table

| Problem | Root Cause | Effect | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| No dependency array | `useEffect` runs every render | Exponential listener accumulation | Add `[]` |
| No cleanup function | `return` statement missing | Listeners survive unmount, prevent GC | Return cleanup that calls `removeEventListener` |
| Anonymous handlers | New function reference each time | `removeEventListener` silently fails | Assign handlers to named `const` variables |
| Stale `lastScrollY` closure | State captured at effect creation time | Direction always compares against `0` | Move to `useRef` |

The corrected component registers exactly **2 listeners total**, they are correctly removed when the component unmounts, and the scroll direction comparison is always accurate regardless of how long the component has been mounted.

